bug.short_desc: AnnotationValue.toString is creating incorrect and truncated text that cannot be used in source code

long_desc.thetext: bug is not only since e4.4 it is also in 4.3, 3.8
Created attachment 245995 Proposal to show a possible solution

The attached AnnotationUtil.java is a work-around that achieves more or less the expected result, but it is however not nicely integrated into the eclipse apt that way.
I hope it helps to find a quick solution to incorporate into the eclipse jdt apt kit.
Thanks for the hints, Ivan. No promise yet, but I will take a look at during Marks time frame.

ok for me.

I just saw the incoming changes in the two AnnotationValueImpl#toString(), and I wondered why there's no escaping for char and String literals.
Shouldn't they use something like org.eclipse.jdt.core.dom.StringLiteral#setLiteralValue(String) and org.eclipse.jdt.core.dom.CharacterLiteral#setCharValue(char)?

(In reply to Markus Keller from comment #11) > I just saw the incoming changes in the two AnnotationValueImpl#toString(), > and I wondered why there's no escaping for char and String literals.
I don't get what you meant by string literals. You didn't mean StringLiteral, do you?

Thanks for mentioning your example project again. I wasn't aware that you made it trivial to set up and test this. BTW: To avoid the full system path in AnnotationProcessorTest, you can just change the method to this and then run as a Java Application:
public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception { File bundleDir = new File("."); ...
I've confirmed now that the escaping is indeed missing in JDT. Reopening to get that fixed.
I've fixed existing code that implements escaping and provided a reusable helper method with bug 442614: org.eclipse.jdt.internal.compiler.util.Util#appendEscapedChar(StringBuffer, char, boolean)
